Apply ENIGMA to resolve latent cell type specific states

Weixu Wang

2021/9/15

Introduction

This tutorial introduce how to use ENIGMA to resolve cell type-specific expression (CSE) profile and benchmark ENIGMA with other methods. We hope use ENIGMA could help us detect cell type-specific sample-wise correlation structure to decipher latent cell expression heterogeneity on population level.

Simulate CSE and constitute in silico mixture

To show ENIGMA could resolve the signal, we first use splatter to simulate the CSE with specific clustering structure.

# loading the packages we need
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(scater))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(splatter))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ENIGMA))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(cowplot))

## Simulate CSE
params <- newSplatParams(seed=2022)

                                     group.prob = c(0.25,0.25,0.25,0.25),

We could see that the first CSE have four distinct clusters, and third CSE have two clusters. I also simulate CSE (second CSE) with subtle variations across clusters. Then I simulate cell type-specific fractions, and doing linear combinations with CSE to construct bulk-samples

sim.groups.c1 <- counts(sim.groups.c1) %*% diag(10000/colSums(counts(sim.groups.c1)))
sim.groups.c2 <- counts(sim.groups.c2) %*% diag(10000/colSums(counts(sim.groups.c2)))
sim.groups.c3 <- counts(sim.groups.c3) %*% diag(10000/colSums(counts(sim.groups.c3)))
    
colnames(sim.groups.c2) <- colnames(sim.groups.c3) <- colnames(sim.groups.c1) <- paste0("Sample-",1:ncol(sim.groups.c1))

mat <- list(sim.groups.c1,sim.groups.c2,sim.groups.c3)
names(mat) <- c("ct1","ct2","ct3")
H1_array <- array(0,
                  dim = c( 3,
                           8368,
                           200))

### construct reference profile
H1 <- array(0,
                  dim = c( 3,
                           8368))
for(i in 1:3){
  H1_array[i,,] <- mat[[i]]
  H1[i,] <- rowMeans(mat[[i]])
}

k <- 3 # number of cell types
ng <- 8368 # number of genes
p <- 200 # number of samples

###Simulate cell type-specific fractions
cc <- matrix(runif(p*k), ncol=k)
cc <- t(scale(t(cc), center=FALSE, scale=rowSums(cc)))
colnames(cc) <- paste('cellType', 1:ncol(cc), sep="")


##evaluate differential expression genes
##calculate 
G <- NULL
for(i in 1:200){
    G <- cbind(G, t(as.matrix(t(as.matrix(cc[i,])) %*% H1_array[,,i])))
}

I also add some noise to the expression profile to make this task harder.

noise <- t(matrix(rnorm(p*ng)*15, ncol=ng))
noise[noise<0] <- 0
G <- G + noise
k <- apply(G,1,var) > 10^-8
G <- G[k,]
H1 <- H1[,k]
H1_array <- H1_array[,k,] 

rownames(G) <- colnames(H1) <- paste0("gene",c(1:nrow(G)))
colnames(G) <- paste0("Sample",1:ncol(G))
rownames(H1) <- colnames(cc)

Finally, I have construct a bulk expression profile, and each CSE in this profile has latent clusters structures. Now lets see that whether we could detect the clusters structure on bulk sample levels.

raw <- SingleCellExperiment(assays=list(logcounts = G))
raw$Group <- label.c1                
raw <- raw
raw <- runPCA(raw)
p <- plotPCA(raw, colour_by = "Group")

raw$Group <- label.c2
p_raw2 <- plotTSNE(raw, colour_by = "Group",point_size=3)

raw$Group <- label.c3
p_raw3 <- plotTSNE(raw, colour_by = "Group",point_size=3)

p_raw <- plot_grid(p_raw1,p_raw2,p_raw3,nrow=1)
p_raw <- p_raw + ggtitle("Pseudo-Bulk") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
p_raw

We could see that the bulk samples could not reveal any CSE specific clusters, suggest that the bulk expression profile would corrupt some biological meaningful signal.

Using other methods to deconvolve bulk RNA-seq samples

Before I use ENIGMA to perform deconvolution, I first use TCA to perform deconvolution so that to support the superior performance of ENIGMA TCA is a deconvolution methods require input mixture profile and cell type fraction matrix. To run this algorithm, I first used robust linear regression model to fit the cell type specific fraction matrix.

get_proportion <- function(X, ref) {
    cat( date(), "Calculating cell type proportion of bulk samples... \n" )
    gene_id = intersect( rownames(X), rownames(ref) )
    X_m = X[gene_id,]
    ref_m = ref[gene_id,]
    ref_m <- apply(ref_m,2,scale)
    theta <- NULL
    coefVec <- NULL
    for(i in 1:ncol(X_m)){
        Exp <- as.matrix(X_m[,i])
        rownames(Exp) <- rownames(ref_m)
        colnames(Exp) <- colnames(X_m)[i]
        Exp <- scale(Exp)
        
        rlm.o <- rlm(Exp ~ as.matrix(ref_m), maxit = 100)
        coef.v <- summary(rlm.o)$coef[2:(ncol(as.matrix(ref_m)) + 1), 1]
        coefVec <- rbind(coefVec,coef.v)
        coef.v[which(coef.v < 0)] <- 0
        total <- sum(coef.v)
        coef.v <- coef.v/total
        theta <- rbind(theta,coef.v)
    }
    colnames(theta) <- colnames(coefVec) <- colnames(ref_m)
    rownames(theta) <- rownames(coefVec) <- colnames(X_m)
    res <- list()
    res$theta <- theta
    return(res)
}
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(MASS))
Fra_Simulate <- get_proportion(G, t(H1))
## Wed Sep 15 11:03:01 2021 Calculating cell type proportion of bulk samples...

Using ENIGMA to resolve bulk samples

To use ENIGMA infer CSE, I first build a ENIGMA object.

G <- as.matrix(G)
H1 <- as.matrix(H1)
egm = create_ENIGMA(bulk = G, ref = t(H1), ref_type = "bulk", meta_ref = as.matrix(colnames(t(H1))))
## Wed Sep 15 11:05:22 2021 Reference from FACS Bulk RNA-seq/microarray.
